    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1940-05-29T21:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1940-05-29T21:00:00-05:00" n="557"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d557">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94112/368: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul General at Hankow</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Spiker</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Hankow</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1940-05-30T10:00:00+08:00"
                            >May 30, 1940—10 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received May 30—4:15 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>42. Reference my 34, April 30, 3 p.m. Japanese military liaison officer here has
                    stated that restrictions on travel on the Yangtse by third power nationals have
                    been lifted. Japanese Consulate General <pb facs="0533" n="525" xml:id="pg_525"
                    /> has today indicated further steps are being taken in relation to the
                    transportation to Shanghai of Americans now awaiting passage.</p>
                <p>Repeated to Chungking, Peiping and Shanghai.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Spiker</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
